The English translation of "Un capitalisme de favoritisme à l'américaine" is:  "Ameri-can-style favoritism capitalism"   Or more naturally in English:  "American-style crony capitalism"  This phrase suggests a form of capitalism that involves favoritism or preferential treatment for certain individuals or groups, often implying unfair advantages or corruption.
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the American Treasury Department and its IMF allies pushed the blame for the problems in that region onto favoritism capitalism, lack of transparency, and an inefficient government?
The countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the authority of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed much more rapidly than any other region - and with greater stability - over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal brings a new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "One must be without fault to criticize another."
Enron used large-scale accounting gimmicks and complicated financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its true value.
There is no transparency here.
She used her money to acquire influence and power, shape US energy policy, and avoid regulations.
The capitalism of favoritism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of one party.
The former American Secretary of the Treasury, Robert Rubin, would have tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards definition office attempted to clean up the accounting records of senior executives' perks.
It was partly thanks to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was impeded.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is merely a thin shield for the well-being of old companies: giving favors to those who have good connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed speaks to the absence of favoritism in capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it attests to the importance of free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to investigate Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
The contributions to the campaigns were not simply in the public interest, but constituted an investment.
As with most of Enron's investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but it did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some relate to politics: the Enron scandal reinforces arguments in favor of campaign financing reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests that in fact can buy elections.
However, the Bush administration refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in the formulation of its energy policy.
Other lessons focus on the economy, particularly on information economics.
For markets to function and for appropriate signals aimed at effectively allocating resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: the owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as rosy a picture as possible.
The account control is intended to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guardians?
Who will control the account controllers?
We count greatly on the motivations.
The accountants wish to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and account control leads to other distorted motivators: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of the controls could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unknown hero of the debacle.
But the accounting firms and their corporate clients – not surprisingly, given the backlash that has developed – have fiercely attacked his proposal to separate advisory activities from accounting and auditing functions.
What Levitt understood – and what the collapse of Enron so clearly demonstrated – is that motivations are important, but that unfettered markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
Markets cannot provide motivations for creating wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron implemented.
The new economy - and its newly complicated financial instruments - highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make it easier to muddy the waters.
Instead of confronting the problems, the America of business turns systematically away from them, supported and encouraged by American-style favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our time consists in finding the right balance between government and market.
The status quo will assert that Enron was an exception: that its disappearance was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must face the consequences and will face them.
But the great majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors declare that its central practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act in the same manner.
They are right - and that is the problem.
Investors need to be assured that the information received adequately reflects the economic situation of a company.
Within the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors currently have no possibility of being offered these guarantees.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we may never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motives.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They affirm that they manage conflicts of interest, but we observe that they manage them in their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new venues for abuse are created time and again – take, for instance, the repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act in the United States, which had separated commercial banking from investment banking.
We have repeatedly witnessed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated market liberalization.
We now need to resist the temptation to lean towards the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
